% Outer Themes 
% An outer theme specifies what the “outside” or “border” of the presentation slides should
% look like. It specifies whether there are head- and footlines, what is shown in them, whether there is
% a sidebar, where the logo goes, where the navigation symbols and bars go, and so on. It also specifies
% where the frametitle is put and how it is typeset.
\NeedsTeXFormat{LaTeX2e}
\ProvidesPackage{beamerouterthemewhubeamer}[2024/12/21 v3.1.1 whubeamer outer theme]
% SJTU VI Library
\RequirePackage{whuvi}

% 16.2 Outer Themes
% An outer theme dictates (roughly) the overall layout of frames. It specifies where any navigational elements
% should go (like a mini table of contents or navigational mini frames) and what they should look like. Typically,
% an outer theme specifies how the following elements are rendered:
%   • The head- and footline.
%   • The sidebars.
%   • The logo.
%   • The frame title.
% 7.7 SJTU VI Library
